  <!-- LOCAL KNOWLEDGE -->
  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">Local knowledge</p>
    <h2>The Macedon Ranges — Cold Country Where Chimneys Work Hard</h2>
    <div class="local-box">
      <p>The Macedon Ranges is one of the coldest parts of Victoria within reach of Melbourne — and one of the most chimney-dependent. The elevated terrain running from Gisborne and Riddells Creek in the south through Woodend, Kyneton and up toward Daylesford and Hepburn Springs in the north creates a landscape where winter frosts are common from April and heating season runs a full five months. Temperatures drop hard overnight across the Ranges, and wood heating isn't supplemental — it's how most homes here stay warm.</p>
      <p>The housing stock reflects this. Kyneton and Woodend have some of the best-preserved Victorian and Edwardian bluestone and brick architecture outside of Melbourne — properties with original open fireplaces and masonry chimneys that are decades old and see sustained heavy use every winter. Across the broader Ranges, there are farmhouses, acreage properties and heritage homesteads that have been burning wood for generations. We service this area as part of our regular Macedon Ranges run and know the local housing stock well.</p>
      <p>The Daylesford and Hepburn Springs pocket at the northern end of the Ranges — which we also cover — is a different profile again: a high concentration of holiday homes, short-stay rentals, bed and breakfasts and weekender cottages where the heater sits idle for months then gets used heavily during visits. That irregular pattern is actually harder on a flue than consistent regular use, and we regularly find significant creosote buildup in holiday properties that were last cleaned two or three seasons ago.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cold-warning">
      <div class="cold-warning-icon">&#10052;&#65039;</div>
      <div class="cold-warning-body"><strong>Macedon Ranges cold warning:</strong> At elevation the Ranges gets genuine frosts — sometimes snow at Mount Macedon and the higher country. Cold flue downdraught is very common here on winter mornings. If your fire smokes back when you first light it, prime the flue first: hold a lit rolled newspaper inside the firebox for 30–60 seconds before loading the heater. If the problem is consistent regardless of temperature, the flue needs a professional clean.</div>
    </div>
  </section>

